{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/introduction-to-image-processing-with-python-histogram-manipulation-for-beginners-8b107d4c4fef", "time": 1683018071.053937, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/introduction-to-image-processing-with-python-histogram-manipulation-for-beginners-8b107d4c4fef/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Introduction to Image Processing with Python | by Tonichi Edeza | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Introduction to Image Processing with Python", "description": "In this lesson, we learn how to adjust images by interpolating the Cumulative Distribution Function of their greyscale intensities. This is a vital tool for any data scientist working with images\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["In this lesson, we learn how to adjust images by interpolating the Cumulative Distribution Function of their greyscale intensities. This is a vital tool for any data scientist working with images.", "As always, first we must import the required libraries.", "Let\u2019s begin by loading an image with obvious lighting issues.", "The above image has some clear lighting issues, but we should be able to correct this using the power of Python.", "One common way of handling lighting issues is through Histogram Manipulation. In essence, what we do is first convert the image to greyscale.", "We then have to extract the image\u2019s value histogram.", "It is very clear that this histogram does not resemble a normal distribution. You might be tempted to try and snap this distribution into a normal distribution. However there is a slightly more intuitive way to handle this issue.", "Remember that the theoretical Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF) for a normal distribution is a straight line. This being the case, it is better to snap the CDF of our image into a straight line.", "To do this, we can make use of the interpolate function in NumPy.", "We can now then use the interpolation to help us adjust the actual CDF.", "As we can see, the CDF is much closer to the target CDF. However, to see if this was truly helpful we must view the actual image.", "We see that the adjustment we made to the CDF has had quite a significant effect on the image. We can now see details that were previously hidden in the shadows. To wrap this all up, let us create a function which will adjust the CDF of any image we feed it.", "Since we have created a function, we can now simply call it and feed it any image that we want to adjust.", "Note that we can also bypass the greyscale conversion all together and adjust the colored image directly.", "We should note however that it may not be as effective compared to the greyscale converted image. However from a purely aesthetic standpoint it is quite interesting.", "Histogram manipulation can be a tricky processes. Snapping the CDF of your image to a straight line is just one of many ways to make the image more palatable for our human eyes. On that note, that there is no hard rule that states that you must convert the CDF into a straight line. Sometimes it may be best to snap it into a sinusoidal line or even a sawtooth line. The key is that the image becomes easier for us humans to understand.", "To practice, I would encourage you to try it out on some images you have taken. I was amazed at how many little details the machine could actually pick up on.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Just a kid that writes about data and the world."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F8b107d4c4fef&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fintroduction-to-image-processing-with-python-histogram-manipulation-for-beginners-8b107d4c4fef&source=post_page---two_co